<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[264,1324,1353,1899]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,466,1513,1539]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Diagnosis.—</emphasis>
Males are characterised by the large tegular apophysis (TA) arising basally (
<figureCitation box="[364,451,1553,1579]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 52. 41 – 46" captionStartId="21.[264,383,1727,1751]" captionTargetBox="[272,1313,422,1692]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[264,1323,409,1701]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 52. 41 – 46. Pellenes montanus. 41, abdomen of male, dorsal view; 42, abdomen of female, dorsal view, 43, palpus of male, ventral view; 44, palpal tibia of male, retrolateral view; 45, epigynum, ventral view; 46 spermathecae, dorsal view. 47 – 52. Synageles canadensis. 47, palpus of male, ventral view; 48, palpal tibia of male, retrolateral view; 49, palpal tibia of male, prolateral view; 50, epigynum, ventral view; 51, spermathecae, ventral view; 52, spermathecae, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273391/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Fig. 
<number box="[420,451,1553,1579]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="43.0">43</number>
</figureCitation>
) and the shape of the retrolateral apophysis (RTA) (
<figureCitation box="[1069,1160,1553,1579]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 52. 41 – 46" captionStartId="21.[264,383,1727,1751]" captionTargetBox="[272,1313,422,1692]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[264,1323,409,1701]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 52. 41 – 46. Pellenes montanus. 41, abdomen of male, dorsal view; 42, abdomen of female, dorsal view, 43, palpus of male, ventral view; 44, palpal tibia of male, retrolateral view; 45, epigynum, ventral view; 46 spermathecae, dorsal view. 47 – 52. Synageles canadensis. 47, palpus of male, ventral view; 48, palpal tibia of male, retrolateral view; 49, palpal tibia of male, prolateral view; 50, epigynum, ventral view; 51, spermathecae, ventral view; 52, spermathecae, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273391/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Fig. 
<number box="[1126,1160,1553,1579]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="44.0">44</number>
</figureCitation>
). Females are characterised by the chevron pattern on the abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[912,1002,1593,1619]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 52. 41 – 46" captionStartId="21.[264,383,1727,1751]" captionTargetBox="[272,1313,422,1692]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[264,1323,409,1701]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 52. 41 – 46. Pellenes montanus. 41, abdomen of male, dorsal view; 42, abdomen of female, dorsal view, 43, palpus of male, ventral view; 44, palpal tibia of male, retrolateral view; 45, epigynum, ventral view; 46 spermathecae, dorsal view. 47 – 52. Synageles canadensis. 47, palpus of male, ventral view; 48, palpal tibia of male, retrolateral view; 49, palpal tibia of male, prolateral view; 50, epigynum, ventral view; 51, spermathecae, ventral view; 52, spermathecae, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273391/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Fig. 
<number box="[969,1002,1593,1619]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="42.0">42</number>
</figureCitation>
), the presence of a median hood­like pocket (arrow, 
<figureCitation box="[566,653,1633,1659]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 52. 41 – 46" captionStartId="21.[264,383,1727,1751]" captionTargetBox="[272,1313,422,1692]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[264,1323,409,1701]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 52. 41 – 46. Pellenes montanus. 41, abdomen of male, dorsal view; 42, abdomen of female, dorsal view, 43, palpus of male, ventral view; 44, palpal tibia of male, retrolateral view; 45, epigynum, ventral view; 46 spermathecae, dorsal view. 47 – 52. Synageles canadensis. 47, palpus of male, ventral view; 48, palpal tibia of male, retrolateral view; 49, palpal tibia of male, prolateral view; 50, epigynum, ventral view; 51, spermathecae, ventral view; 52, spermathecae, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273391/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Fig. 
<number box="[622,653,1633,1659]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="45.0">45</number>
</figureCitation>
) and the elongated, parallel spermathecae (S) (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 52. 41 – 46" captionStartId="21.[264,383,1727,1751]" captionTargetBox="[272,1313,422,1692]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[264,1323,409,1701]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 52. 41 – 46. Pellenes montanus. 41, abdomen of male, dorsal view; 42, abdomen of female, dorsal view, 43, palpus of male, ventral view; 44, palpal tibia of male, retrolateral view; 45, epigynum, ventral view; 46 spermathecae, dorsal view. 47 – 52. Synageles canadensis. 47, palpus of male, ventral view; 48, palpal tibia of male, retrolateral view; 49, palpal tibia of male, prolateral view; 50, epigynum, ventral view; 51, spermathecae, ventral view; 52, spermathecae, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273391/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Figs 
<number pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="45.5" valueMax="46.0" valueMin="45.0">45– 46</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="20.[264,1324,1353,1899]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,499,1713,1739]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Distribution.—</emphasis>
From Québec (present records) to Alberta, with a record from Colorado. The few known specimens suggest that the species is boreal with a southern extension in the Rockies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[264,1324,1353,1899]" lastBlockId="21.[264,1323,284,350]" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,448,1833,1859]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Remark.—</emphasis>
The Jamésie record given here comes from a naturally burned Black Spruce forest. The species was never collected again in any other habitat despite an intense sampling effort in that region. 
<bibRefCitation box="[621,871,284,310]" pageId="21" pageNumber="36" refString="Larrivee, M., Hahring, L., &amp; Drapeau, P. (2005) Effects of a recent wildfire and clearcuts on ground-dwelling boreal forest spider assemblages. Canadian Journal of Forest Research, 35, 2575 - 2588." type="journal article">
Larrivée 
<emphasis box="[727,778,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">et al</emphasis>
. (
<number box="[801,863,284,310]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="2005.0">2005</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
report the occurrence of the species in the province without details.
</paragraph>
